---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { SEGMENTS } from '../../data/segments';
import { APPS } from '../../data/apps';

const path = '/for';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'for');
const desc = description(site, 'for');

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Why sort Shopify email tools by store type instead of one master ranking?',
    answer: 'A vinyl shop and a wholesale climbing-gear distributor have nothing in common except Shopify checkout. Store-type guides pull the right tools off the shelf for your catalog rhythm — drop cadence, replenishment windows, account onboarding — instead of forcing every merchant through the same feature matrix.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Sequenzy top every store-type shelf?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy sits at slot one on most vertical guides because lifecycle strategy and pay-per-email pricing fit lean Shopify teams running real retention programs. Klaviyo earns the lead when predictive data depth at volume is the binding constraint. ActiveCampaign wins when CRM pipelines share the sales desk with ecommerce. Each guide documents where to swap the default pick.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How many tools belong on a serious shortlist?',
    answer: 'Five is the right bin size: your vertical default, a data-heavy alternative, a fast-setup option, a capture specialist if list growth is the bottleneck, and one workflow or CRM wildcard. Each store-type page names all five. Expand the shortlist only for managed services, POS loyalty, or compliance workflows that generic rankings ignore.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When do I read a vertical guide versus the full tool catalog?',
    answer: 'Open /apps when you want the complete 21-tool comparison with pricing and feature depth. Open /for/[store-type] when you already know your catalog and need lifecycle priorities, segment metrics, and ranked picks tuned to how your customers actually buy — not a one-size-fits-all leaderboard.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why include popup and SMS tools in an email catalog?',
    answer: 'Some shelves hold complementary gear. Privy completes the capture layer before lifecycle email takes over. Postscript handles SMS recovery when inbox timing is too slow. We rank primarily on email lifecycle capability because education, nurture, and replenishment still anchor most Shopify retention stacks.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the most expensive mistake when picking an email tool?',
    answer: 'Buying the loudest brand instead of the right fit. Klaviyo is exceptional at 3,000 orders per month and overbuilt at 200. Shopify Email handles broadcasts fine but cannot run consumption-based replenishment. Match the tool to the retention job your catalog produces, the way you would match a nib size to your handwriting — not buy the most expensive pen in the case.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How often do vertical rankings get refreshed?',
    answer: 'We update when pricing tiers, Shopify integrations, or positioning shift materially. Each guide carries ArticleSchema with dateModified. Revisit quarterly, or sooner when order volume crosses a tier that changes your send economics or segmentation needs.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can one store belong to more than one vertical?',
    answer: 'Often. A beauty brand running subscription boxes should read both guides and prioritize skip recovery alongside replenishment timing. Jewelry with high AOV overlaps two consideration-heavy shelves. Start with your primary revenue model, then borrow priorities from adjacent guides where catalog behavior overlaps.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Where do use-case guides fit after I pick a vertical?',
    answer: 'Store-type pages tell you which tools to audition. Use-case pages at /use-cases/ tell you how to wire specific flows — welcome, cart recovery, replenishment, winback — once the platform is chosen. Think of vertical guides as shelf labels and use-case guides as assembly instructions.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Catalog index · by store type</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Shopify email tools, filed by what you sell</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
        A master ranking treats every Shopify store like the same product on the shelf. It is not. A supplement merchant needs compliance-safe replenishment the way a tea shop needs harvest-date education — same category label, different brewing instructions. A jewelry catalog needs eight-week nurture; a print-on-demand shop needs forty-eight-hour activation. This hub is the card catalog: twelve vertical drawers, each with tools ranked against the retention friction your catalog actually creates.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
        Every drawer holds a standalone research pass — comparison tables, tool profiles, segment playbooks, FAQs. Sequenzy leads most shelves because agent-first lifecycle strategy and pay-per-email economics fit growing teams without enterprise overhead. Each guide also names when Klaviyo, ActiveCampaign, Omnisend, Privy, or a specialist deserves the top slot instead.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Full tool catalog</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/compare">Comparison hub</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases">Use-case guides</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      title="How to browse this catalog"
      picks={[
        { label: 'Drawer 1', tool: 'Find your vertical', reason: 'Open the card below that matches your catalog — fashion, beauty, supplements, jewelry, home goods, food & beverage, pet products, digital products, print-on-demand, high-AOV, subscription boxes, or B2B wholesale.' },
        { label: 'Drawer 2', tool: 'Read the shelf label', reason: 'Each guide opens with five picks tuned to that vertical\'s buying rhythm, pain points, and email priorities — the TL;DR before you read the full spec sheet.' },
        { label: 'Drawer 3', tool: 'Compare 17 tools', reason: 'Vertical comparison tables filter the full catalog to what matters for your retention job, like pulling only waterproof shells from a climbing-gear wall.' },
        { label: 'Drawer 4', tool: 'Build the flows', reason: 'Jump to /use-cases/ for welcome, cart recovery, replenishment, and winback playbooks once you have chosen a platform.' },
        { label: 'Default shelf', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Ranked first on most verticals for agent-first lifecycle strategy and pay-per-email pricing — audition Klaviyo when Shopify data depth at scale is the primary criterion.' },
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Your catalog changes what "best" means</h2>
      <p>
        On a spec sheet, Shopify email tools look interchangeable — automations, segments, templates, Shopify sync. In the field, the hard problems are catalog-specific. Fashion merchants wrestle seasonality and size variants the way keyboard enthusiasts debate switch weight and actuation force: the same category, incompatible preferences. Supplement brands navigate compliance and consumption cycles like specialty tea sellers track harvest windows and steep times. Digital product shops compress activation into forty-eight hours. B2B wholesalers onboard accounts that may sit dormant for weeks after approval.
      </p>
      <p>
        Crown one tool "best overall" without store context and you mislead the buyer — like recommending a broad nib fountain pen to someone who writes pocket notes in cramped margins. Klaviyo's predictive CLV transforms operations at three thousand orders per month and becomes shelf bloat at two hundred. Privy is essential capture infrastructure for trend-driven POD traffic and irrelevant noise for established wholesale account lists. ActiveCampaign's CRM pipelines matter for consultative jewelry sales and barely register for impulse POD purchases.
      </p>
      <p>
        The guides below treat each vertical like a curated tool wall: what breaks first, how customers buy, which email jobs matter this quarter, which metrics prove quality, and which five tools to audition before committing budget. Every page links to <a class="link" href="/apps">full tool profiles</a>, <a class="link" href="/compare">head-to-head comparisons</a>, and <a class="link" href="/use-cases">use-case playbooks</a> for assembly after purchase.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-14">
    <p class="catalog-kicker">All 12 vertical drawers</p>
    <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Pull the drawer that matches your catalog</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-lg text-[#4a2d17]">Each link opens a standalone guide with 2,000+ words of vertical-specific research — filed separately, not keyword-swapped from a template.</p>

    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      {SEGMENTS.map((seg) => (
        <a class="card group" href={`/for/${seg.slug}`}>
          <p class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-[#9a5b16]">{seg.name}</p>
          <h3 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f] group-hover:text-[#9a5b16] transition-colors capitalize">
            {seg.slug.replace(/-/g, ' ')}
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[#5d3a1d]">Pain points: {seg.pain}</p>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm font-bold text-[#9a5b16]">Open this drawer →</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Shelf standards</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">How we rank tools per vertical</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3 text-[#4a2d17]">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Lifecycle fit</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7">Does the tool handle the vertical's primary email job — replenishment, long nurture, account activation, drop orchestration — without duct-tape workarounds?</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Shopify signal depth</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7">Can it read the product, order, and behavioral data the vertical demands — variants, subscriptions, collection browse, account status?</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Operating weight</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7">Can a lean team tune flows weekly, or does every change require agency hours and a three-week ticket queue?</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-8 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Sequenzy tops most vertical shelves because it balances lifecycle fit and operating weight — agent-first strategy, pay-per-email economics, playbooks from welcome through winback. Klaviyo wins when Shopify data depth at scale is the bottleneck. ActiveCampaign wins when CRM overlap dominates the sales desk. Each store-type page documents the exceptions in plain language, not footnotes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Shared hardware</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">What every Shopify store gets right first</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Vertical differences aside, durable email programs share the same foundation kit: suppression before creative polish (never collide welcome with cart with post-purchase), revenue quality over vanity clicks (margin and repeat purchase beat open rate), lifecycle moments mapped to Shopify events before tool shopping begins. The vertical guides assume these basics — see <a class="link" href="/">homepage methodology</a> and <a class="link" href="/use-cases/segmentation">segmentation guide</a> for the shared playbook.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Four catalog clusters emerge from the twelve drawers. <strong>Replenishment shelves</strong> — beauty, supplements, food, pet — optimize consumption timing and subscription state. <strong>Consideration shelves</strong> — jewelry, home goods, high-AOV — optimize long nurture and trust proof. <strong>Velocity shelves</strong> — fashion, POD, digital — optimize speed, activation, and trend windows. <strong>Account shelves</strong> — B2B wholesale, subscription boxes — optimize lifecycle state machines. Identify your cluster, read your guide, then cross-read adjacent verticals if your catalog spans multiple.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="mb-8 flex items-end justify-between gap-6">
      <div>
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Top shelf · quick reference</p>
        <h2 class="mt-3 text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Email tools that appear across verticals</h2>
      </div>
      <a class="link" href="/apps">Full rankings</a>
    </div>
    <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">
      {APPS.slice(0, 8).map((app, i) => (
        <a class="ledger-card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>
          <span class="rank-pill">{i + 1}</span>
          <h3 class="mt-3 font-black text-[#24170f]">{app.name}</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">{app.bestFor}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-[#24170f]/10 bg-[#24170f] py-14 text-[#fffaf1]">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-[0.28em] text-[#fbbf24]">Card catalog · all 12 guides</p>
      <h2 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl font-black">Vertical index at a glance</h2>
      <dl class="mt-10 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/fashion" class="hover:underline">Fashion</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Drops, variants, seasonal winback</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/beauty" class="hover:underline">Beauty</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Replenishment, routines, subscriptions</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/supplements" class="hover:underline">Supplements</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Compliance, consumption, subscriptions</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/jewelry" class="hover:underline">Jewelry</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Gift timing, trust, long nurture</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/home-goods" class="hover:underline">Home goods</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Room projects, inspiration, cross-sell</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/food-and-beverage" class="hover:underline">Food & beverage</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Reorder, launches, subscriptions</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/pet-products" class="hover:underline">Pet products</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Life-stage, consumption, onboarding</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/digital-products" class="hover:underline">Digital products</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Activation, cross-sell, renewal</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/print-on-demand" class="hover:underline">Print-on-demand</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Trends, margin, personalization</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/high-aov" class="hover:underline">High-AOV</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Trust, financing, consultation</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/subscription-boxes" class="hover:underline">Subscription boxes</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Previews, skip recovery, churn</dd></div>
        <div><dt class="font-black text-[#fbbf24]"><a href="/for/b2b-wholesale" class="hover:underline">B2B wholesale</a></dt><dd class="mt-1 text-[#f5dfbd]">Accounts, bulk reorder, rep follow-up</dd></div>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">When to trade up — or trade out</h2>
      <p>
        Vertical guides name starting points, not lifetime contracts. Common upgrade paths read like gear progression on a climbing wall: Shopify Email → Sequenzy or Omnisend when automations become daily work; Omnisend → Sequenzy or Klaviyo when subscription or segmentation complexity outgrows the interface; Privy-only capture → add a lifecycle platform when list size exceeds conversion capacity; Mailchimp → Sequenzy when ecommerce segmentation becomes operational, not occasional; Sequenzy → Klaviyo when predictive analytics and agency ecosystem justify profile-based pricing at your send volume.
      </p>
      <p>
        Upgrade signals vary by vertical but rhyme across catalogs: email revenue flatlines despite list growth, flows need weekly manual surgery because the catalog changed, subscription or account logic exceeds current tool capability, or per-contact billing exceeds pay-per-email economics at your actual send patterns. The <a class="link" href="/compare">comparison hub</a> supports head-to-head decisions at each inflection point.
      </p>
      <p>
        Do not migrate reactively after one bad month. Audit lifecycle coverage first: which moments lack automation, which segments receive conflicting messages, which metrics declined. Migration without operational clarity recreates the same mess on a shinier dashboard — like swapping keyboard switches without fixing your typing posture.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">What shifts on each shelf</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Fashion</strong> prioritizes drop orchestration, variant back-in-stock, and seasonal winback before clearance. Sequenzy leads on strategy; Klaviyo on variant data; Privy on pre-drop capture. <a class="link" href="/for/fashion">Fashion drawer →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Beauty</strong> runs on replenishment timing, routine education, and subscription skip recovery. Shade matching and bundle attach separate winners from generic ecommerce tools. Yotpo enters when reviews and loyalty sit at the center of the stack. <a class="link" href="/for/beauty">Beauty drawer →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Supplements</strong> layer compliance-safe education and consumption-based reorder on top of beauty-like replenishment logic. Drip and Brevo enter for workflow control and budget discipline respectively. <a class="link" href="/for/supplements">Supplements drawer →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Jewelry</strong> and <strong>high-AOV</strong> extend consideration to weeks or months — trust content, financing, gift calendars, consultation follow-up. ActiveCampaign rises when CRM overlap matters. <a class="link" href="/for/jewelry">Jewelry →</a> · <a class="link" href="/for/high-aov">High-AOV →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Home goods</strong> sells room projects over individual SKUs — inspiration series, cross-sell by completion, life-event triggers. Mailchimp appears for legacy retailers migrating gradually. <a class="link" href="/for/home-goods">Home goods drawer →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Food & beverage</strong>, <strong>pet products</strong>, and <strong>subscription boxes</strong> share consumption and subscription math but diverge on perishability, life-stage segmentation, and box preview choreography. Rejoiner rises for managed subscription retention. <a class="link" href="/for/food-and-beverage">Food →</a> · <a class="link" href="/for/pet-products">Pet →</a> · <a class="link" href="/for/subscription-boxes">Boxes →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Digital products</strong> compress activation into forty-eight hours — delivery, onboarding, cross-sell, renewal. ActiveCampaign rises for coaching and high-ticket digital. <a class="link" href="/for/digital-products">Digital drawer →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Print-on-demand</strong> optimizes trend speed and margin discipline — Privy for capture, Firepush for flash urgency, strict discount guardrails. <a class="link" href="/for/print-on-demand">POD drawer →</a>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>B2B wholesale</strong> replaces cart recovery with account activation, bulk reorder cadence, and rep coordination. ActiveCampaign and Sequenzy split CRM and lifecycle duties. <a class="link" href="/for/b2b-wholesale">B2B drawer →</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="ledger-card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Selection matrix</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Match tool to primary criterion</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full min-w-[640px] text-left text-sm text-[#4a2d17]">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/15 text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-wider text-[#9a5b16]">
              <th class="py-3 pr-4">If your priority is…</th>
              <th class="py-3 pr-4">Start with</th>
              <th class="py-3">Also audition</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8"><td class="py-3 pr-4">Lifecycle strategy without bloat</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold">Sequenzy</td><td class="py-3">Klaviyo, Omnisend</td></tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8"><td class="py-3 pr-4">Maximum Shopify data depth</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold">Klaviyo</td><td class="py-3">Sequenzy, Sendlane</td></tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8"><td class="py-3 pr-4">CRM + sales pipelines</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold">ActiveCampaign</td><td class="py-3">Sequenzy, Klaviyo</td></tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8"><td class="py-3 pr-4">Fast multichannel setup</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold">Omnisend</td><td class="py-3">Sequenzy, Firepush</td></tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8"><td class="py-3 pr-4">List capture before lifecycle</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold">Privy</td><td class="py-3">+ Sequenzy or Klaviyo</td></tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-[#24170f]/8"><td class="py-3 pr-4">Managed expert help</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold">Rejoiner</td><td class="py-3">Sequenzy self-serve</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="py-3 pr-4">Tight budget</td><td class="py-3 pr-4 font-bold">Brevo or Sequenzy</td><td class="py-3">tinyEmail for campaigns only</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="card">
      <p class="catalog-kicker">Assembly order</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Same build sequence, different parts per vertical</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Regardless of store type, assemble lifecycle email in this order: (1) post-purchase and delivery confirmation, (2) welcome series for non-buyers, (3) browse and cart recovery with suppression rules, (4) vertical-specific retention — replenishment, nurture, box preview, or account onboarding, (5) winback, (6) VIP and promo campaigns. Jumping to step six produces revenue spikes that collapse when discounts stop — like buying a display case before you have records to file. Each store-type guide names what step four means for that catalog.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Budget two to four weeks per step on Sequenzy or Omnisend; four to eight weeks on Klaviyo or ActiveCampaign when data hygiene and integration complexity run high. Avoid platform migrations during Q4 unless emergency — stabilize flows in Q1 through Q3 when the catalog team can actually test sends.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Twelve separate research passes, not twelve template swaps</h2>
      <p>
        Each store-type page was written as a standalone retention brief — filed independently, not generated from a master template with swapped keywords. Fashion research drew on drop cadence patterns from apparel merchants running six or more collections per year. Supplement research incorporated compliance workflow interviews with brands using legal review gates before send. B2B wholesale research mapped Shopify Plus company account fields to email trigger requirements. Digital product research focused on activation drop-off in the first forty-eight hours post-purchase.
      </p>
      <p>
        That independence matters because search intent diverges: "Shopify email tool for subscription boxes" is not "Shopify email tool for jewelry" with different adjectives. The buyer problems, metrics, and tool tradeoffs fork early. A single ranked list forces false precision — Klaviyo as number two everywhere — when the real question is whether you need Klaviyo's data depth, ActiveCampaign's CRM, Privy's capture, or Sequenzy's lifecycle strategy for your specific catalog this quarter.
      </p>
      <p>
        Start here to route yourself. Read one guide deeply. Audition the five named tools against your order volume, team capacity, and current stack. Build flows from <a class="link" href="/use-cases">use-case guides</a>. Compare finalists in <a class="link" href="/compare">head-to-head comparisons</a>. Return to this hub when you expand into adjacent verticals — many Shopify merchants add subscription, wholesale, or digital product lines and need to merge email priorities from multiple drawers.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold">
      <a class="link" href="/apps">All Shopify email tools →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison hub →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/use-cases">Use-case guides →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Why this catalog exists</h2>
      <p>
        Merchant search intent is vertical-specific. "Best email tool for Shopify subscription box" is a different query than "best email tool for Shopify jewelry" — different buying cycles, metrics, failure modes, and tool tradeoffs. This hub exists because a single master ranking cannot serve both the tea merchant tracking harvest education and the mechanical keyboard shop orchestrating group-buy waitlists. Ranking Sequenzy first on most guides reflects lifecycle strategy priority for growing merchants, not sponsorship. Klaviyo, ActiveCampaign, Omnisend, Privy, Rejoiner, and others win clearly in scenarios documented inside each drawer.
      </p>
      <p>
